'''Arthur Joseph''' "'''Monkey'''" '''Gould''' (10 October 1864&nbsp;<U+2013> 2 January 1919) was a Welsh international [[rugby union]] [[Centre (rugby union)|centre]] and [[Fullback (rugby union)|fullback]] who was most associated as a club player with [[Newport RFC|Newport Rugby Football Club]]. He won 27 [[Cap (sport)|caps]] for [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]], 18 as captain, and critics consider him the first superstar of Welsh rugby. A talented all-round player and champion sprinter, Gould could side-step and kick expertly with either foot. He never ceased practising in order to develop his fitness and skills, and on his death was described as "the most accomplished player of his generation".{{sfn|Wanganui Chronicle}}

Following the withdrawal of their regular fullback, Newport RFC first selected Gould in 1882, when he was 18. He was never dropped from the side thereafter and played regularly until he retired in 1898. Gould played for Newport during their "invincible" season of 1891<U+2013>92, when they did not lose a match, and scored a record 37 [[try|tries]] in Newport's 24-game 1893<U+2013>94 season, a club record that still stands. Gould frequently travelled due to his job as a public contractor, and consequently turned out for a number of other sides during his career, including the clubs [[Richmond F.C.|Richmond]] and [[London Welsh RFC|London Welsh]], and the county side [[Middlesex Rugby Football Union|Middlesex]].

Gould was first selected for Wales in 1885 when he played at fullback against [[England national rugby union team|England]]. He was awarded the captaincy in 1889, by which time he was playing at centre, and led Wales to their first [[Six Nations Championship|Home Nations Championship]] and [[Triple Crown (rugby union)|Triple Crown]] titles in 1893; that tournament's match against England established Gould as a great player and captain. By the time Gould retired he was the most capped Welsh centre, a record he held until 1980, with 25 caps in the position. He ended his international career against England on 9 January 1897. The game, played in front of 17,000 supporters at [[Rodney Parade]], was Gould's 18th as Wales captain <U+2013> a record eventually broken by [[Ieuan Evans]] in 1994.

Towards the end of his career Gould was at the centre of a controversy known as the "Gould affair" that saw Wales withdraw from international rugby for a year. The controversy centred on the support of the [[Welsh Rugby Union|Welsh Football Union]] (WFU) for a [[testimonial]] for Gould on his retirement. The English [[Rugby Football Union]] and [[International Rugby Board|International Rugby Football Board]] (IRFB) argued that the testimonial constituted professionalism <U+2013> which they claimed breached the sport's by-laws. The WFU withdrew from the IRFB in protest, rejoining a year later under the IRFB-imposed condition that Gould would not represent Wales again. He worked as a brewery representative after retiring from rugby, and died of an internal haemorrhage in 1919 at the age of 54.

==Family and early years==
Arthur Joseph Gould was born into a sporting family in [[Newport, Wales|Newport]], [[Monmouthshire (historic)|Monmouthshire]], on 10 October 1864 to Joseph and Elizabeth.{{sfn|Williams|2004}} His father, from [[Oxford]], England, moved to Newport to find work, setting up his own brass foundry business.{{sfn|Williams|2004}}{{sfn|Richards|1980|p=73}} Joseph was also an ardent sportsman, playing for the local cricket team.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=69}}

Gould's five brothers were all notable rugby players and athletes. His brother [[Bob Gould (rugby player)|Bob]] was a [[Forwards (rugby union)|forward]] who played 136 times for [[Newport RFC|Newport Rugby Football Club]], whom he captained in the 1886<U+2013>87 season.{{sfn|Bob Gould: Profile}} Bob was also capped 11 times for Wales between 1882 and 1887,{{sfn|Bob Gould Wales}} and captained his country once, versus [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] in 1887.{{sfn|Bob Gould: Profile}} A younger brother, [[Bert Gould|Bert]], was a centre who played three times for Wales <U+2013> he appeared with Gould in the Welsh team that won the [[Triple Crown (rugby union)|Triple Crown]] for the first time in 1893.{{efn|A Triple Crown is when one of the four [[Home Nations]] sides defeats the other three during a single championship.{{sfn|Richards|2014}}}}{{sfn|Bert Gould: Profile}} His other brothers <U+2013> Harry,{{sfn|Harry Gould: Profile}} Gus{{sfn|Gus Gould: Profile}} and [[Wyatt Gould|Wyatt]]{{sfn|Wyatt Gould: Profile}} <U+2013> all played rugby for Newport. Wyatt captained Newport in 1905<U+2013>06, and Harry played for them in their inaugural season of 1875<U+2013>76. For the first 29 seasons of its existence, Newport RFC always had at least one of the Gould brothers in the team. Wyatt played for the club until 1907; he also ran the 400m [[Hurdling|hurdles]] for Great Britain in the [[1908 Summer Olympics]].{{sfn|Wyatt Gould}}

The young Gould often climbed trees, and thus acquired the childhood nickname "Monkey", which was soon contracted by most to "Monk".{{sfn|Parry-Jones|1999|p=43}}{{sfn|Marshall|1893}} Like his brother Wyatt, he was a keen athlete and made <U+00A3>1,000 during his years as a rugby player by entering [[track and field]] meets.{{sfn|Williams|2004}}{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=70}} A county champion sprinter and hurdler,{{sfn|Williams|2004}} Gould finished third in the [[Amateur Athletic Association]] 120 yard hurdles in 1887 and 1893.{{sfn|Wyatt Gould}}

== Rugby career ==

=== Club and county history ===
[[File:Arthur Gould, Newport.jpeg|upright=1.35|right|thumb|alt=Profile photograph of Arthur Gould wearing the black and amber hooped shirt of Newport RFC.|Gould in Newport club jersey, ca. 1890]]
At the age of 14 Gould captained the Newport Junior team, and later played a few games for the Third XV.{{efn|A "XV" is a rugby union team (due to the 15 players in a side), and therefore Third XV is the 2nd reserve side.}} Gould was drafted into the First XV <U+2013> the senior team <U+2013> as a [[Fullback (rugby union)|fullback]] at the age of 18.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=69}} On 18 November 1882 Newport had a home fixture against Weston-super-Mare at [[Rodney Parade]]. The Newport groundsman, John Butcher, had been sent by the club to collect the regular fullback who had not appeared for the game.{{sfn|Thomas|1979|p=11}} Gould, who was returning from a youth match, saw Butcher outside the missing fullback's home and approached the groundsman to discover that the player was at a funeral.{{efn|The regular fullback was Fred Dowdall.{{sfn|The 1882<U+2013>83 Season}}}} Butcher offered Gould the position instead, and then the groundsman successfully persuaded the club captain to play him.{{sfn|Thomas|1979|p=11}}{{sfn|The 1882<U+2013>83 Season}} Gould ran in two of his team's three [[try|tries]] after disregarding the instructions of his captain, [[Charlie Newman]], who kept shouting for Gould to "Kick, kick!"{{sfn|Thomas|1979|p=11}}{{sfn|The 1882<U+2013>83 Season}} After this, he was not dropped by Newport until his retirement in 1898.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=69}}

As rugby was then an exclusively amateur sport, Gould and his brother Bob travelled Britain working as public works contractors.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=70}} During this time he entered open athletic meets and played for various English rugby teams including the [[Trojans Rugby Club|Southampton Trojans]], and from 1887 was a regular member of the London side [[Richmond F.C.|Richmond]].{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=69}} In 1885 Gould was invited to play for the newly formed Welsh exiles team [[London Welsh RFC|London Welsh]]. [[London Scottish F.C.]] had been founded for Scottish players working or studying in the city, but until this time a London club for Welsh players had not existed. The side's first game, a trial match, was played on 21 October 1885 at Putney, and three days later the first team played London Scottish at the [[Saracens F.C.|Saracens]]' Palmerston Road ground in Walthamstow.{{sfn|Jones|1985|p=6}} Gould played at half-back, and was joined in the team by [[Martyn Jordan]], [[Thomas Judson]], [[Rowley Thomas]], [[Charles Taylor (rugby player)|Charles Taylor]] and [[T. Williams]] <U+2013> all past or future Welsh internationals.{{sfn|Jones|1985|p=6}} During the 1885<U+2013>86 season London Welsh were invited to form a combined "exiles" team with London Scottish, to face a London XV in a charity match at [[The Oval]]. Gould was one of six Welsh players selected to play in front of a crowd of 8,000 that included the [[Edward VII|Prince of Wales]].{{sfn|Jones|1985|p=8}}
