== Gould affair ==
[[File:Gould affair.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.35|alt=Hand drawn cartoon, titled "Throwing down the Gauntlet". The cartoon depicts three caricatures representing the England, Scotland and Ireland Unions, looking aghast as a figure representing the Welsh Union throws a defiant Gauntlet to the ground. The Welsh Union is applauded by Dame Wales.|''[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]]'' cartoon by [[Joseph Morewood Staniforth]] depicting events of the "Gould affair". The cartoon depicts three caricatures representing the England, Scotland and Ireland Unions, looking aghast as a figure representing the Welsh Union throws a defiant Gauntlet to the ground.]]
By 1896 Gould had played more first class matches, scored more tries and dropped more goals than any other player on record. This led to ''[[South Wales Argus]]'' journalist W. J. Townsend Collins, to write in the paper: "...&nbsp;as Arthur Gould is as pre-eminent in football as [[W. G. Grace]] is in cricket, the footballing enthusiasts of Wales might recognise his services to the game&nbsp;... by some national testimonial."{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=93}}

A Welsh shipbroker, W. J. Orders, organised a collection fund on the floor of the Cardiff [[Coal Exchange]] and floated a public [[testimonial]] of one [[shilling]].{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=93}} The national response was considerable and within weeks the total was into hundreds of pounds. This drew the [[Welsh Rugby Union|Welsh Football Union]] (WFU) into a confrontation with the IRFB, as rule 2 on professionalism stated that no player was allowed to receive money from his club, or any member of his club, for services rendered to football.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=93}} The fund could have been seen as a professional fee to Gould, henceforth making him ineligible to play for his country. The WFU argued that the money raised was not given by the club, but rather an outpouring of thanks from the Welsh public to a national hero.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=94}}

By April 1896 the Welsh Football Union had sanctioned a subscription of 1,000 shillings to be contributed to the Gould testimonial. The [[Rugby Football Union]] (RFU) complained and the IRFB reacted by informing the WFU that only a plate up to the value of a hundred pounds sterling could be given to Gould, and that the remaining funds should be donated to charity;{{sfn|Parry-Jones|1999|p=40}} otherwise Wales would lose their international fixtures. The WFU stood down and withdrew their subscription. The reaction in Wales was one of anger, with the people feeling that the WFU had bowed to English pressure, and had been bullied into a decision against the people's wishes.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=94}} 

In a move that was described as an act of hurt pride by social historian David Smith, but also as a manoeuvre to appease the Welsh supporters, in February 1897 the WFU wrote to the IRFB and withdrew their membership.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=94}} The WFU claimed that they alone had authority over the matter because the IRFB did not have any rules regarding amateurism.{{sfn|Phillpots|2000|p=93}} The WFU then reinstated their subscription to Gould, and on [[Easter Monday]] 1897 a banquet was arranged at Drill Hall in Newport in Gould's honour. Many civic and sporting worthies were in attendance to witness the WFU president [[John Talbot Dillwyn Llewellyn|Sir John Llewellyn]] present Gould with the title deeds of a gift house.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=95}} The 250 guests, including [[David Alfred Thomas, 1st Viscount Rhondda|David A. Thomas]],{{sfn|Richards|1980|p=84}} were joined by a reed and string orchestra, the band of the Fourth Battalion of the [[South Wales Borderers]], and galleries packed by members of the public.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=95}}

Wales did not field an international team until the IRFB, supported by the RFU,{{sfn|Parry-Jones|1999|p=44}} recommended that the WFU be readmitted into the organisation in February 1898. The WFU agreed that they would in future abide by all IRFB by-laws, and that Gould not be allowed to play in any future internationals. Gould accepted the ruling but returned to rugby as a referee{{sfn|Davies|2008|p=327}} and Welsh international selector.{{sfn|Vaughan|1990|loc=chpt. 8}} The compromise prevented a long term split in the sport, and by 1901 the IRFB added laws to the game banning professionalism to clarify their authority on the issue.{{sfn|Phillpots|2000|p=94}}

== Later life and legacy==
[[File:Arthur Gould print.jpeg|right|thumb|alt=Water colour promoting Belgian chocolates that depicts Gould running in a hand-off pose.|Gould's popularity remained after his retirement and he appeared on a variety of merchandise, such as this card promoting Belgian chocolates.]]
After retiring from rugby, Gould became a brewery representative around Newport. He was still a very popular figure and was followed during his work by fans; his image was still worth money, appearing on merchandise such as cigarette cards and matchboxes.{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=69}}

Gould died in 1919, at the age of 54. Falling ill at work on 2 January, he was rushed home where died later that day of an internal [[Bleeding|haemorrhage]].{{sfn|Arthur Gould: Profile}}{{sfn|Wanganui Chronicle}} His funeral was reported as the biggest ever seen in Wales up to that time; it was surpassed three decades later by that of the former British Prime Minister [[David Lloyd George]].{{sfn|Arthur Gould: Profile}} Gould was buried at [[St Woolos Cemetery]], Newport. In reporting his death, ''[[The Times]]'' stated:
{{Quotation|To him more than anyone else is due the rise of Welsh football, and so football as we know it now. He did more than any one else to transform a game from one in which brute force and individual skill were the chief characteristics to one in which scientific combination became the main feature, without the sacrifice of individualism.{{sfn|The Times}}}}

In 1923 a memorial fund was raised in Gould's name, the donations of which were given to the [[Royal Gwent Hospital]] in Newport. The hospital recognised the gift with the Arthur Gould Memorial Bed, inscribed: "To the memory of Arthur Gould <U+2013> Greatest of Rugby Football Players". Though the bed was lost when a portion of the hospital was demolished.{{sfn|Arthur Gould: Profile}} Donations for the memorial, which totalled <U+00A3>1,525, were received from all over the world, and several matches were staged to raise funds, including a fixture between Newport and Cardiff.{{sfn|The Cynic 1923}}

Gould has been described as the first superstar of his sport by rugby historian Terry Godwin while David Smith in the ''Official History of the Welsh Rugby Union'' described him as the first player to surpass national recognition, becoming in both meanings of the word "an international".{{sfn|Smith|1980|p=68}}{{sfn|Godwin|1984|p=9}} The Welsh Academy's Encyclopedia of Wales, published over 90 years after his death, records Gould as "Welsh rugby's first superstar",{{sfn|Davies|2008|p=327}} while a 1919 obituary described him as "the most accomplished player of his generation".{{sfn|Wanganui Chronicle}} He set several long-standing records for his country, including captaining Wales 18 times, a number eventually surpassed by [[Ieuan Evans]] in 1994. Gould played 25 matches at centre for Wales, a record that stood until beaten by Steve Fenwick in 1980.{{sfn|Arthur Gould: Profile}} He was also the most capped Welsh player, with 27, at the time of his retirement.{{sfn|Leach|2007}}

Gould was inducted into the [[Welsh Sports Hall of Fame]] in June 2007;{{sfn|Welsh Sports Hall of Fame}} members of Gould's family were in attendance including his granddaughter Mary Hales. When Newport RFC set up their own hall of fame in 2012 the first person inaugurated was Gould.{{sfn|Newport RFC look at Arthur Gould collection whereabouts}}

